If in doubt, refer to the Handshake which saw the otherwise national resistance movement placated overnight.
A majority of Kenyans, on any given day, want to see one of their own at the long table of eating chiefs. Apparently, the eater does so in their stead, reason why tribal politics may never end soon.
Equally true is the fact that both pre-election and post-election violence are instigated by political kingpins. Those extra seats are supposedly meant to appease these warlords, lest they incite citizens to violence. Bitter truth it is.





So we are caught in what psychologists call approach-avoid conflict, wherein we want as many of our chiefs to sit in government, yet we are not ready to fund their stay there.
Currently, there is jostling over the proposed extra constituencies. What does this say about us? It reminds me of a craze in recent times where every clan wanted to have their own school.
Corruption is suffocating us. However, it hasn’t been accorded as much attention as the BBI Frankenstein and its alleged 14b magic wand. And when some thief is rounded up from our backyard, we demonstrate on streets in solidarity. 
Missile launchers
This reminds me of the place of the youth in all this. Apparently, they are the most pawned. It’s high time the youth stood to be counted or forever hold their peace. Their political inactivity is befuddling.



